ment is not only in\ncrease the number of employes, but to i\nincrease the pay as well. Probably in j\nanother decade, if the militarists have I\ntheir way, we shall find at least 2,-\n000,000 names on the payroll. And if\nwe could now add to the list of the\nnames those employed by private con\ntractors on government and paid in the 1\nmoney appropriated by congress, it I\nis possible the government has 2,000,- 1\n000 dependents now.\n\"This is a tremendous burden for\nthe government to carry. When we\nthink of the vast number of people\nwho find employment under other\nbranches of government, state and lo\ncal, it is probable that the people of\nthe country have upon their hacks an i\narmy of 3,000,000 supported wholly or 1\nin part by taxation.\nThere must be a limit somewhere\nand it is not too soon to begin the\nsearch for places where wholesome n\nt.renchment may be undertaker..\n-o+o\n.NEWSPAPER Pl'FFS.\nisn't it rather strange that the usual\ncomplimentary notice should on the\ncne hand be appreciated and sought\nafter, while on the other it is char\nacterized as a \u201cnewspaper puff?\u201d Edi\ntors know that the average printed\ncompliment has little if any interest\nfor anybody except the person men\ntioned. That the public holds the\nisame view is evident from the term\nc>f contempt applied to it.\nRecognizing this, most editors would\nThe Gospel of Good Cheer\n|t\u00bb I!. Simmons. (Iiiiiriiiiiii of 1 Executive \u00ab*n\u00bb hi it t of the\nNational Prosperity Association of SI. Louis.\ns \\\\V have formed n business organization to.be called [lie Na\ntional Prosperity Association of St. Louis\u2014having for its object the\nonconragenieiii of :i return of prosperity sooner than might other\nwise nee nr wii lion I help, op without some active efforts on the part\nof ihe business men. We believe that present conditions are ex\nceedingly favorable to this. The body\u2014commercial\u2014has been very\nill, and in a sense had typhoid fever, but now the fever has en\ntirely left\u2014the disease is out, and the patient only remains sick\nand weak, so that permanent recovery is only a matter of time.\nHow to quicken ihe recovery in a healthy manner is the problem\nwe are undertaking, and we believe in the power of encouragement\n-by showing to the world at large that conditions are fundamen\ntally sound and healthy, and that nothing now exists but a lack of\nconfidence to restore its to a full measure of prosperity, such as\nexisted a year ago. We are making an effort, through the press and\nthrough other business associations, and through traveling sales\nmen, to encourage the people to see the sunshine that is clearly\nin the pathway,and to believe that things are very much better than\nmost people think they are, and that with the present crop pros\npects soon to he realized, if nothing unforeseen occurs in the imme\ndite future, it is only a question of a very short time until t\u2019he din\nner pails will again be full and the unemployed will again he em\nployed at fair wages, ami that there will he no reduction in wages\nof those already employed. We believe there is a great change of\nsentiment with the intelligent people of the United States, and that\nit is increasing very rapidly. It therefore seems to us a most prop\nitious time to do what we can to encourage a quick return of pros\nperity, to the great benefit of the laboring man and to the benefit of\nall business interests.\nOn all sides we find expressions of favorable sentiments to the\neffect, that further legislation against railroads and large corpora\ntions shall cease, that the business interests of jthis country shall be\ngiven a reef and that the departments of justice may he allowed to\nproceed with their work in a quiet manner\u2014which, of course, is\ngreatly to he desired- It is absolutely essential to the welfare of\nthis country that the railroads should again prosper, because more\nj than one and a half million men are in the employ of the railroads\nj today, and as many more are dependent upon their revenue from\nrailroad investments, hence, it, is almost, impossible that we should\nreturn to a full measure of prosperity excepting the railroads par\nticipating in the same.\nWith the full co-operation of the press of the United States\u2014\nj which we hope to have\u2014and with the united efforts of the business\nassociations of all the large cities, we feel confident of our ability\nto accelerate the speed of returning prosperity to a great degree.\nI It is hardly neccessary to say that everybody would like to have\nI wages maintained at. the highest figure ,and without a cut. There\nI is no doubt as to the wisdom of this course. AVe are most heartily\nI in favor of and are working to 'that end\u2014giving our time and our\nI money to accentuate better conditions and returning prosperity.\nWe hope and expect to have the co-operation of manufacturers,mer\nchants. bankers, railroads and labor element\u2014in fact, every busi\nness interest of the United States. We ask every business man\u2014\nand, in fact, every commercial man and bouse in this country\u2014 to\nlend us (heir a id\u2014to work with us\u2014to join hands in the gospel of\ngood cheer, and scatter seeds of sunshine in the paths of all when\nthey meet. If they are pessimists, we want them to become opti\nmists: if thy are optimists, we want them to increase 'their opti\nmism; we want them to hunt for sunshine; we want them to he\ncheerful in their manner and in their conversations\u2014in their pre\ndictions\u2014in their hopes and aspirations.\nFundamentally, everything is all right\u2014the basis of our pros\nperity comes from the soil, and the products of the soil have never\nhad greater value than at present. The outlook for crops is mar\nvelously promising. To illustrate\u2014the winter wheat crop\u2014which\nis ihe first one of importance that comes to our notice\u2014is better\nthan ever before in the history of the country. Kansas reports a\ncondition of 105 on winter wheat\u2014something heretofore unknown.\nWhen the lumber interests shut down, and the railroads laid off a lot\nof their employes, a large proportion of 'them went immediately to\nthe fanpers, or planters, so that these toilers of the soil have, for\nthe first time in many years, had enough labor to put in a full or\nlarge crop\u2014perhaps a larger crop than ever before, and the planting\nis still going in. With a larger planting than has ever before, and\nwith favorable weather, it seems reasonable to suppose that we\nmay have excellent crops this year\u2014it looks exceedingly probable.\nTherefore, everything which is to restore confidence\u2014so that the\nwheels of commerce begin to move again with the same rapidity\nthat they did a year or two ago, when we were at the height of our\nprosperity, and from which we went in a wonderfully short time to\na very low stage of depression and hard times.\nAVe ask the co-operation of everybody in the Unite:! States in\nibis movement\u2014which we think has great merit, which has great\npossibilities.\n\n\n\nv\n\n\nprefer To exclude the eomplimenta sy\naltogether. Some of them resolve to\ndo it. and yet it is one of the most\ndifficult rules to observe consistently.\nAn advertiser paints his store or puts\nin a new show window, makes a pub\nlic subscription to charity or a public\nspeech on a popular subject. In what\nis intended to be merely a news item\nthis advertiser is referred to as a pro\nperous merchant or our public spirited\nfellow townsman, and tlie bars at\ndown. The editor and the adverti\nknow it is merely a newspaper puff,\ndoing neither any real good, but the\npasture is open to ever\\ forager s\ning to feed bis vanity on newspap v\nnotoriety.\nThe editor, having mentioned one t\nvertiser, feels the obligation to per\nform the same service for all as op\nportunity may offer. Hut complimen\ntaries cannot be confined to advertis\ners. A friend of the paper secret\ncherishing political ambition manages\nto tret his name in print, opening th>\nway for every reader to expect a\ncomplimentary notice\nThen the editor is in for it. Th n\nfollows the long s; of personals\nwhich mean nothing to anybody\ncept [he person mentioned and his\nfamily and the eternal vigilance re\nquired by the editor lest some vaim i\nsubscriber be overlooked. Of com\nthere is persona', intelligence which is\ninteresting and worthy of publication,\nbut should it not be considered from\nthe standpoint of its news value and\nnot a complimentary notice? Will it\nbe interesting to a considerable num\nber of the paper's readers? Is it\nworth publication if the desire to\nplease the person mentioned be elioT\nnated? Sound editorial judgment\nwould seem to require an affirmed'.\nanswi-v m these questions.\u2014America i\nPress.\n-0<4*p\nLAFAYETTE LODGE\nHOLDS MEETING\nThe meeting last .Monday night was\na most interesting one. The library j\ncommittee made an encouraging re\nport. The delegates to the Grand j\nLodge made a written report of the;\nproceedings of that body at its late\nconvention. Oflicial circulars Nos. j.\nand h of the Grand Chancellor rela\ntive to A better lodge attendance,\u201d j\nNew .Membership,\" \"Avoid suspen-1\nsions,\u201d \"A list of the new Deputy\nGrand Chancellors for each lodge\u201d!\nand expressing a desire that all lodges\nin this Domain comply with Section\n\u201d\u25a009 of the Supreme Statutes establish\ning a memorial day and asking all\nlolges to hold proper memorial ser\nvices on that day. Also a list of the j\nGrand Lodge officers for 190S-1909-\nThat beautiful second rank was con- j\nferred on two pages after standing an j\nexamination in ;he secret work of the j\nfirst rank. One new petition for mem-\nership by initiation was received.\nThe first and third ranks will be con\nferred next Monday night in the am\nplified form. If may interest those\nmembers who do not attend very regu\nlarly o know that this lodge is going\nto give a banquet and that certain qual\nifications will he necessary to put\ntheir fee: tin lor the table on this occa\nsion. Try and be one the ban\nqueters. It's easy.\n\u2014Why not let McDaniel k Baugh\nman give you an estimate on your\nwindow and door frames and all kinds\nof inside finish. Phone SOC. f-31-lm\nHeart to Mean\nTalks.\nBy EDWIN A. NYE.\n(V[ yr:;. I. UK\u00bbS, v I \\<iwin .A. N\\>.\nTIIE FACES OF THE DEAD\nA touching slory comes from Buffalo.\nYears ago a father iost his only son, a\nlad of twelve* years.\nWhen a longing for a sight of the\nboy's absent face comes over the man\nhe stands by the school gate and\nwatches the face of every child. He\nnever sees the faee he looks for; but,\ncheered by the composite face of boy\nhood, he takes tip his work again.\nPathetic? Aye, and there is a great\nteaching in the story, and consolation.\nIn the picture gallery of almost every\nsoul there is the frame of some dear\nface it shall never see again The\nmind's eye holds the portrait hut dim\nly. The years ate so thick a veil lie\ntween! But betimes, when the noises\nof the world are still and memory is\nquick to do its office, we almost see\nthem once again\u2014the faces of our\nloved and lost.\nAh, the faces!\nMost of all do we see them in our\nsleep. No able artist can retouch the\nfaded pictures like the artist of kindly\nsleep. And how changed the faces!\nThey were pale, worn faces upon\nwhich one day we dropped our bitter\ntears. But. lo, these dream faces are\nbeauteous, winsome, smiling, as if they\nbeheld seme work of love begun, some\ndeed of kindness doue!\nThe faces of the dead!\nWhen we seek to find their counter\npart in the faces of the living or in\nthe faces of our dreams we are cheered\nand strengthened. The dead would\nhave it so. They would be remember\ned. Aye, but in that remembrance\nwere they to speak their greatest wish\nthey would have their memory conse\ncrated to the good of the living. And\nso as we go chastened to our daily task\nby the remembrance of the dead we\nfind refreshment by the way. And the\nworld is thus made better. Ail boy\nhood is dearer to that father in Buffalo\nbecause he fiuds reminders of the face\nifce lost.\nThe faces of the dead!\nWho would bring pain or sorrow to\nthose dead faces fashioned so like our\nown?\nO son of man, be careful lqst when\nyou torture the h?art and distort the\nfaces of your fellows you come face to\nface wiih the sacred features of your\ndead!\nCASTOZIZA.\nBfnr* tie _ >?The Kind Yon Have Always Bought\nBigcattie\nI Why Worry Over j\na Hot Stove?\nLeave off biscuit and try some\nof Skidmore's nutritious Hot I\nRolls. They are baked daily.\nGet the habit and drive by every\nafternoon at 5 o'clock for Hot\nRolls for supper and a nice loaf\nof bread for breakfast- Cakes\nbaked to order.\nT. H. SKidmore\n1102 WEST SECOXD ATESCE.\nSKIM-CURE SOAP\nFor the Bath\nRrefersbing and invigorating.\nFor the Scap\nCleansing the scalp.\nFor the Hands\nHealing and softening to the\nskin.\nFor the Nursery\nPerfectly pure and specially\nmedicated.\nFor the Complexion\nBeautifying to the complexion.\nSOLD BT ALL DRUGGISTS.\nManufactured by\nDr.\nMcCammon\n\nSON\nI LYE BLUFF, AES\nthe long\ndistance\nfacilities\nOf this Company bare been m,Urlw\nadded to, thus Insuring a more p-\nefficient and comprehensive\nthan heretofore. Nearly every T*\"\nof Importance In Texas and Arkan1**\nand adjoining States, Including qJ*\nhoma and Indian Territory, c&0\nreached over our lines and'those!*\nCompanies with whom we connect\nTHK SOUTHWESTERN\nTELEGRAPH TELEPRoin\nCOMPART,\nBUSTER\nBROWN\nBLUE\nR.IBBON\nSCHOOL\nSHOES\nFor Sale at\nMullikin\u2019s\nDepartment Store\n326-32S\nMeJn-Street\nAre Your Kidneys Well?\nBright's Disease, Diabetes,\nRheumatism, Gout, Gravel,\nDropsy, Inflammation of tlio\nBladder, Bad Blood, and Ner\nvous Troubles caused by Sick\nKidneys.\nSeawell and Ancrum, the well\nknown Druggists, will guaran\ntee that \u201cHindipo\u201d will benefit\nin al